featured_reviews.review_id: Established around AD 1740 by the Tuluka cavalry force of Kayamkulam Maharaja... Originally erected inside the mud fort where the Tuluka soldiers were keeping their weapons and guarding the frontiers. When King Marthandavarma conquered Kayamkulam, the fort lost its relevance, but the mosque continued to flourish because of Rawther tradesmen who began to settle here in large numbers. The mosque was later rennovated by the famous Tamil tradesman Vilayil Tharakan and subsequently by the muslim Rawther community which settled here. This is now the biggest Rawther mosque in the whole of south Kerala. Attached to the mosque lies the Durgha of famous Soofi saint - Shaik Mohiyideenul Khadiri - of Kottar, Kanyakumari, who selected this place as his favourite and used to stay here on his routine Islamic preaching missions.

featured_reviews.review_id:
The jumamasjid is hundreds of years old and was renovated several years ago. The woodwork of the old mosque is very beautiful. Very beautiful place, beautiful masjid all this is the specialty of the small village of clappana. There are many ways to reach this mosque on Ochira Vallikavu Road. Kannan pally road can also be reached at the jumamasjidh.

The famous ancient houses of pally kizhak Kannanpally  muri , Mukkadayil and Cheruthara,Perur, eravi mangal,  karipuram are  Located in clappana village. They were the ones who maintained this mosque in the early days. Since there is a lot of paddy land, they are the ones who provide food to the masjid . In the old days.

featured_reviews.review_id: This masjid is located on the side of the National Highway at Kayamkulam. We have prayed here many times while travelling. There is a separate ladies' musalla. The toilets are also kept very clean. There is also a small parking space in front of the masjid. Overall, a very good masjid when you are travelling via Kayamkulam.
